/*
 Older notes from the parent version:

 by ollj
 goal is to allow for high render distance and high detail close to the camera
 goal is to allow for hall of mirror reflections for as long as there are steps left, 
  scatterable non-fake reflections.
 goal is to see the shadow in the reflection of a revflection of a reflection...
 goal is to have any fragment converge in the same linear time
  where closer surfaces simply get more detail/reflections.
 Idealy a top down perspective gets the same fps than a set with an infinite horizon!
 practically, there is still a difference of 60to5 fps, but i am slowly getting to 40to40; ..
 Ambient Occlusion calculatons are draining most resources.

Below methods causes raymarching to converge more linearily
 for many very different fragments of very different scenes
  While it also "warps space" towards the ray, the more steps have been taken.
 Surfaces close to the camera have low epsilon, high precision, lots of reflections.
 Surfaces far from the camera have less precision, less reflections, higher epsilon
 Surfaces/hallways that are nearrly coplanar to a ray 
  no longer have the problem of "running out oof steps" AT ALL.

LONG RENDER DISTANCE;
Heuristic root solving either converges too slowly or too quickly.
if (converges too quickly) you could have more detail == larger distances instead.
Ideally you want to modify them so that all possible cases converge roughly equally.
This is achieved by defining MAX_DIST and MAX_STEPS as non-static float pools
 that diminish with each raymarchng step,
If (any pool drains below 0) the raymarching ends before MAX_HARD iterations.
 heuristic root solving is eigher likely [too divergend] or [converging too slowly]
 these 2 extremes are constrained by draining MAX_DIST and MAX_STEPS.
Doing many small steps drains the 2 pools reciprocally-DIFFERENTLY from, the other 
 than doing many large steps!
Both with one (reciprocal) factor, both pools converge "much more equally" 
 depending on "scene openness" because they drain by the same factor.

RECURSIVE REFLECTION;
If (a ray hits a reflective wall) it keeps raymarching a bounched ray.
 The loop sums up a total color as sum of all reflected rays.
A reflected ray makes up a smaller fraction of the total color.
If (that fraction is too small) no morere flecting of this ray happens,
Finally, the last reflected fraction of a color is added; 
 if (we run out of steps) that is "sky" or "ground" color.
Todo, make that =mix(SkyOrGroundColor,gradientColor,reasonablyScaledDistanceToGradient)

BALLACHE OF PRECISION
 (nearby) reflections need high precision of they distort too much.
 DynamicEps methods insist on low precision, tent to be very "noisy"
 Depending on a points distance to camera, 
  it use a differet (conditions) to determine if (a point is near a surface).
 p+=SurfaceNormal; is a necessary compromise between fast and good recursive reflections.
*/


